So for this broadcast, I thought we'd review some of the improvements we've seen just since World War II.

00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:01.740
That's the period most of us are familiar with.

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:05.740
Now some of you will be hearing about these things for the first time.

00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:11.740
Others will live live through it all. And for them, it'll bring back fond memories.

00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:19.990
So let's go back. It'll be fun. I call this part, do you remember when?

00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:27.990
Before World War II. And for a number of years after that, many congregations didn't have a kingdom hall of their own.

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:33.990
And they were actually encouraged to meet in private homes or in rented facilities.

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:39.990
The thinking was that if you were in a rented facility or a private home, you had more flexibility.

00:03:39.990 --> 00:03:44.990
You could move the meeting place from one place to the other very easily.

00:03:44.990 --> 00:03:50.990
But there were problems or a drawbacks. Sometimes the space would be shared with other organizations.

00:03:50.990 --> 00:03:58.990
So you couldn't leave your literature, magazine, speaker stand, and maybe even a sound system in the hall at the end of the meeting.

00:03:58.990 --> 00:04:03.990
When the meeting was over, you'd have to pack it all up and take it away.

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:06.990
But that's not all.

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:14.990
Sometimes you had to arrive very early and click the place up after a particularly rowdy group of people had used it.

00:04:14.990 --> 00:04:18.990
And if there were cigar smokers in that group, you were in trouble.

00:04:18.990 --> 00:04:23.990
It was very difficult to air the place out in time for the meeting.

00:04:23.990 --> 00:04:28.990
Now remember, in those days, people could smoke in a private hall.

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:34.990
And you could smoke in an airplane. They could smoke almost anywhere. So this was a real problem for us.

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:42.990
There were other problems. Before we had a kingdom hall in my hometown, the congregation met in a rented facility.

00:04:42.990 --> 00:04:46.990
Now in October, the place was decorated for Halloween.

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:52.990
And in December, there was a great big Christmas tree on the platform. We couldn't move it.

00:04:52.990 --> 00:05:00.990
And now this was in Canada. And portraits of the king and queen of England, as well as the British flag, were permanent fixtures in the hall.

00:05:01.990 --> 00:05:04.990
You couldn't remove any of it for the meeting.

00:05:04.990 --> 00:05:12.990
Yet, to their credit, many interested persons attended our meetings. And to them, it wasn't the meeting place that was important.

00:05:12.990 --> 00:05:16.990
It was what they were learning there that counted.

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:23.990
Speaking of our meeting places, at first congregations were on their own when it came to building them.

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:35.990
Now at times, the most a congregation could afford was to purchase the land. And sometimes, that land would sit there for years, because it would take years to get the money together to build the hall.

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:42.990
And then, once they had the money together, were there enough brothers who could take the lead in the construction?

00:05:42.990 --> 00:05:49.990
Sometimes on a weekend, you see just one or two brothers working away at the side of the new hall.

00:05:49.990 --> 00:06:04.990
It had to love them for their perseverance. Nowadays, our kingdom hall construction is supervised by the LDCs with lots of qualified volunteers and practical kingdom halls can be constructed in a short period of time.

00:06:04.990 --> 00:06:14.990
What about the meetings? For years, the ministry school, service meeting, congregation book study, and watchtower study were all about an hour at length.

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:28.990
So were the public talks when we had them. Not first, a public talk wasn't scheduled every week. It would be a series of four or eight talks if you could schedule that many speakers.

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:32.990
And then for a while, the congregation wouldn't have a public talk.

00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:43.990
What was that? Remember, the Theocratic ministry school didn't get underway until 1943, and it took time for the brothers to develop the skills to deliver an hour talk.

00:06:44.990 --> 00:06:49.990
But in time, they were delivering excellent public talks.

00:06:49.990 --> 00:07:05.009
And do you remember when we had individual handbills for each public talk, with the name of the speaker printed on them? Until 1959, only brothers were enrolled in the school.

00:07:05.009 --> 00:07:13.009
For some years, during the first few minutes of the school, there was a rule call. And the names of all the brothers enrolled in the school were read out.

00:07:14.009 --> 00:07:23.009
Now, when your name was read out, you were to answer present. A few rebels would say, here, but you were supposed to say present.

00:07:23.009 --> 00:07:33.009
Now, initially, according to the instructions, if anyone was deliberately and habitually absent over a period of time, he was dropped from the school.

00:07:33.009 --> 00:07:37.009
Later, that was discontinued.

00:07:37.009 --> 00:07:51.009
Now, the rule call arrangement got me into a bit of trouble. You see, in our congregation, when the role was being called each week, I noticed that there were a few young brothers who were just a little bit older than I was, who would answer present.

00:07:51.009 --> 00:07:58.009
So one night, after the school, I asked the school servant if I could have my name read out at the next meeting.

00:07:58.009 --> 00:08:10.009
He warmly commended me, and sure enough, I got my name read out the following week. Everyone congratulated me after the meeting. Couldn't understand why. I only said present.

00:08:10.009 --> 00:08:20.009
Problem was, I didn't know that when you got your name read out, you were agreeing to give a talk. I thought I was just signing up to have my name read out.

00:08:20.009 --> 00:08:32.009
Well, a couple of months later, on April 8, 1953, I delivered my first eight-minute talk on the theme, proclaiming the world's doom.

00:08:32.009 --> 00:08:40.009
Now, why an eight-minute talk? Well, we didn't have Bible readings yet. So, when you were on the school, you were giving an eight-minute talk.

00:08:40.009 --> 00:08:48.009
Well, today, we make sure everyone understands what's involved in being a student in the midweek meeting.

00:08:48.009 --> 00:08:57.009
In 1950, we received the New World Translation of the Christian Greek Scriptures in English, and we were encouraged to bring it to the meetings.

00:08:57.009 --> 00:09:06.009
So, for the Hebrew Scriptures, you'd have the American Standard Version or the King James Version, mostly the American Standard Version because it had Jehovah's name.

00:09:06.009 --> 00:09:16.009
So, you'd have two Bibles to bring to the meeting. There's the one for the Hebrew Scriptures, and then the New World Translation for the Greek Scriptures. Two Bibles, it wasn't too bad.

00:09:16.009 --> 00:09:30.009
But later, the New World Translation of the Hebrew Scriptures was released in installments. So, you'd get a volume every year or two, and as we received each new volume, we were encouraged to bring it to the meeting.

00:09:30.009 --> 00:09:46.009
How in time, those volumes started to pile up. So that by 1960, you might have volumes one through five of the Hebrew Scriptures, and the Greek Scriptures, and your regular study aids, and we had thick study aids in those days.

00:09:46.009 --> 00:09:57.009
We had big briefcases and strong backs in those days. We were really happy to get the complete New World Translation in just one volume in 1961.

00:09:57.009 --> 00:10:11.179
Now, let's say a word about music. That's something that's near and dear to my heart. For many years, it was left up to the local servants to decide which songs the congregation would sing at the meeting.

00:10:11.179 --> 00:10:18.179
So, the chairman of a particular meeting would select the songs, but his choice wasn't always final.

00:10:18.179 --> 00:10:30.179
Many Kingdom Halls had a piano or some other instrument to accompany the singing, but often the musician couldn't play all the songs in the book. So, we'd have to sing the songs he could play.

00:10:30.179 --> 00:10:38.179
We got to know those few songs really well, but those humble musicians did their best to accompany our singing.

00:10:39.179 --> 00:10:47.179
As a result of all this, the words to those songs we sang nearly 70 years ago still come readily to mind.

00:10:47.179 --> 00:10:52.460
Do you remember the written review? Maybe you don't.

00:10:52.460 --> 00:11:00.460
Congregations periodically had a written review of material Edmund covered in the ministry school over the previous weeks.

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:16.460
Now, we had a half hour to answer about 25 questions, but then when the half hour was up, we would write our name on the paper, hand it into the school servant, and he would take all the papers home to grade them.

00:11:16.460 --> 00:11:28.460
Now, if there were 25 questions, you'd get four points a piece for each correct answer, a hundred points total, and then a week later, he'd return the papers to us at the meeting.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:36.460
Now, in the early years of the arrangement, I remember well. He'd announced the highest and lowest grade to the congregation.

00:11:36.460 --> 00:11:41.460
Now, thankfully, he didn't mention the names of the one who got the highest and lowest score.

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:46.460
Later, that arrangement to announce the highest and lowest grade was discontinued.

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:53.460
Do you remember when circuit assemblies began on Friday evening and continued through Sunday afternoon?

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:58.460
A full program was presented Saturday afternoon and evening.

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:01.460
There was never a dull moment on Saturday night.

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:07.779
There were lively demonstrations that kept our interest right up to the end of the program.

00:12:07.779 --> 00:12:11.779
Sometimes, the sets were very elaborate.

00:12:11.779 --> 00:12:16.779
For example, suppose a publisher was demonstrating a presentation from door to door.

00:12:16.779 --> 00:12:20.779
Not today, we just imagine there was a door.

00:12:20.779 --> 00:12:30.779
But back then, at the circuit assembly, there might be a frame with a painted door on the stage and maybe even a doorbell for the publisher to ring.

00:12:30.779 --> 00:12:37.779
Now, if the householder was supposed to be interested, you knew it, because the house number was 777.

00:12:37.779 --> 00:12:45.779
And if the householder was going to be opposed, you knew that as well, because the house number would be 666.

00:12:45.779 --> 00:12:52.779
Now, on one program I remember, the publisher knocks on the door and a brother dressed as a priest answers.

00:12:52.779 --> 00:12:55.779
He puts up a real argument about the Trinity.

00:12:55.779 --> 00:13:02.779
Talk about visual aids, but you never forgot what you saw and heard.

00:13:02.779 --> 00:13:09.779
And do you remember when each congregation had a congregation servant and up to seven other servants?

00:13:09.779 --> 00:13:21.779
The assistant congregation servant, the Bible study servant, the account servant, the watchtower study servant, the magazine territory servant, the literature servant, and the ministry school servant.

00:13:21.779 --> 00:13:29.779
Now, at that time, apart from book study conductors, you couldn't have more than eight servants in the congregation.

00:13:29.779 --> 00:13:36.779
So, unless someone moved, a young man had no chance of becoming a servant.

00:13:36.779 --> 00:13:40.779
So, how could a young man reach out for more responsibility?

00:13:40.779 --> 00:13:46.779
And, how would the prophecy recorded at Micah 5.5 ever be fulfilled?

00:13:46.779 --> 00:13:55.779
There, Jehovah promised, we will raise up against him seven shepherds, yes, eight princes of mankind.

00:13:55.779 --> 00:14:05.779
Well, seven represents completeness, so eight princes, I would indicate that there would be more than enough men in the congregations to provide theocratic direction.

00:14:06.779 --> 00:14:12.779
But how could that be when there was basically a limit of eight servants for congregation?

00:14:12.779 --> 00:14:16.779
The answer came in 1971.

00:14:16.779 --> 00:14:28.779
We were thrilled when we understood that each congregation has a body of elders, and there is no set number of elders or ministerial servants, as many as are qualified can be appointed.

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:39.120
Now, when I was baptized 66 years ago, it didn't have to be approved for baptism by the congregation.

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:46.120
And the only questions asked of baptism candidates were the two they answered at the conclusion of the baptism talk.

00:14:46.120 --> 00:14:57.120
That led to a few strange situations, on a few occasions, much of the surprise of the servants, someone would rush up to the front of the hall at the end of the baptism talk,

00:14:57.120 --> 00:15:02.120
answer the two questions, and get baptized.

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:05.120
Something more was needed.

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:12.120
Assurance that the individual really knew what he was doing, and especially that he was living in harmony with scriptural principles.

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:24.120
So, in 1967, questions were provided, so that the responsible brothers could be assured that each candidate was truly qualified for baptism.

00:15:24.120 --> 00:15:33.120
Those questions have been refined over the years, and today we go over some 60 questions with baptism candidates.

00:15:33.120 --> 00:15:37.120
The copper has turned to gold.

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:41.120
Do you remember when there were very few pictures in our publications?

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:46.120
And the few we had, usually in black and white, are only two colors.

00:15:46.120 --> 00:15:52.120
Today, our spiritual food is served in attractive publications in full color.

00:15:52.120 --> 00:16:04.879
Now, those of us who have served in four language congregations will also remember when a new publication in English might not be available in another language for several years.

00:16:04.879 --> 00:16:08.879
Study articles, trailed by several months.

00:16:08.879 --> 00:16:13.879
That's before it became possible for the branches to do simultaneous printing.

00:16:13.879 --> 00:16:15.879
So, here's how it worked.

00:16:15.879 --> 00:16:21.879
Material in English would be mailed to the branches, regular mail, for translation.

00:16:21.879 --> 00:16:30.879
And if the translators had a question about the meaning of a sentence in English, they would use regular mail to send their question to headquarters.

00:16:30.879 --> 00:16:34.879
In time, headquarters would answer back by regular mail.

00:16:34.879 --> 00:16:41.879
And this back and forth, it could take quite a while, and in some countries, mail service was poor.

00:16:41.879 --> 00:16:50.879
Now, today, thanks to special computer programs our brothers have developed and the ability to communicate electronically and some other factors,

00:16:50.879 --> 00:16:55.879
we're able to release most language editions simultaneously with the English.

00:16:55.879 --> 00:16:59.879
What an improvement.

00:16:59.879 --> 00:17:08.880
Now, speaking of our literature, do you realize that it's been some 31 years since the decision was made that in the United States,

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:12.880
we'd no longer ask for a contribution for our literature?

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:15.880
Later, the arrangement was extended worldwide.

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:20.880
That's been a real blessing for our brothers.

00:17:20.880 --> 00:17:31.880
For example, when we were asking for contributions for literature, some brothers in Africa and other places couldn't afford to have a watchtower for every member of the family.

00:17:31.880 --> 00:17:35.880
They were just too poor.

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:38.880
And what about bomb books?

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:40.880
Tell you an experience.

00:17:40.880 --> 00:17:47.880
In one African country, a missionary noticed that a young brother quoted a wide variety of scriptures in his comments.

00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:54.880
And he got curious. One day he asked the young brother, how did you come to know so many scriptures?

00:17:54.880 --> 00:18:00.880
The brother replied, it's the reasoning book. I read it every chance I get.

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:05.880
The missionary asked him, what do you mean you read it every chance you get?

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:11.880
Well, he replied, I don't have a reasoning book myself. I could never afford one.

00:18:11.880 --> 00:18:16.880
But I know a sister who has one. And she lets me borrow it from time to time.

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:20.880
I read it every chance I get.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:23.880
Well, you can imagine.

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:29.880
Missionary went out and bought him a reasoning book and a new world translation for good measure.

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:34.880
It was a great investment. The young brother was later called into Bethel.

00:18:34.880 --> 00:18:38.880
And where do you think he was assigned to the literature department?

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:49.380
The brothers knew he appreciated the literature so much that he had made sure the congregations had the literature they needed.

00:18:49.380 --> 00:18:54.380
Well, looking back, we can see that the arrangements back then served a purpose.

00:18:54.380 --> 00:18:57.380
They were like fine copper.

00:18:57.380 --> 00:19:00.380
We do not look down on them.

00:19:00.380 --> 00:19:05.380
Rather, we take the view expressed at Zechariah 4 verse 10.

00:19:05.380 --> 00:19:10.380
Who has despised the day of small beginnings?

00:19:10.380 --> 00:19:14.380
There was those taking the lead to saw a better way of doing things.

00:19:14.380 --> 00:19:19.380
They didn't hesitate to make adjustments. That's very faith strengthening.

00:19:19.380 --> 00:19:23.380
And the best is yet to come.

00:19:23.380 --> 00:19:29.630
As I mentioned in the beginning, this may be the first time that some of you have heard about these things.

00:19:29.630 --> 00:19:35.630
Why not ask someone who has been in the truth for many years, what it was like when he was new in the truth?

00:19:35.630 --> 00:19:40.630
That could lead to a very stimulating discussion.

00:19:40.630 --> 00:19:45.630
Thank you for those historical insights, David.

00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:50.630
When you think about how much has changed just in our lifetimes,

00:19:50.630 --> 00:19:57.630
you really see how Jehovah keeps improving his organization.

